**Organists**

Organist and Master of the Choristers: Christopher Stokes. Sub Organist: Geoffrey Woollatt.
Notable [previous organists](/List_of_musicians_at_English_cathedrals) include Edward Betts (d.1767), [Joseph John Harris](/Joseph_John_Harris) (1848–1869), [Frederick Bridge](/Frederick_Bridge) (1869–75), [Sydney Nicholson](/Sydney_Nicholson) (1908–1919), [Norman Cocker](/Norman_Cocker) (1943–1954), [Allan Wicks](/Allan_Wicks) (1954–1962), and [Gordon Stewart](/Gordon_Stewart_(organist)) (1981–1992).

**Choir**

The 1421 statutes for the collegiate church mandated an endowed choir of [lay clerks](/Lay_clerk) and [singing boys](/Choir). These endowments were reaffirmed when the college was re-established after the Reformation. Despite the proximity of two [grammar schools](/Grammar_schools) – [Manchester Grammar School](/Manchester_Grammar_School) and [Chetham's Hospital School](/Chetham%27s_School_of_Music) – from the 17th century onwards, there was no dedicated choir school until the 20th century. Dedicated choir school premises were only constructed by [Percy Worthington](/Percy_Worthington) in 1934. This school did not reopen after wartime damage. Consequently, in 1969, when Chetham's School was re-established as a specialist music school, scholarships were created to enable boys aged 8–13 to join the cathedral choir. These scholarships were later revised in the 1970s to include both girls and boys, making it the first statutory choir in the Church of England to adopt this change. The choir currently comprises 20 choristers and 6 lay clerks.

